SECTION 1 ◆ FORWARD PROXY (The Client's Representative)
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

1.1 THE BASICS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
▸ Simple
  A Forward Proxy sits in front of the CLIENTS (users).
  When you are in an office/school and they use a proxy, that's a Forward Proxy.

  [YOU] ───► [FORWARD PROXY] ───► [INTERNET]

▸ Key Features (Intermediate)
  - IP Masking: The website sees the Proxy's IP, not yours.
  - Content Filtering: Blocks "bad" websites (e.g., blocking YouTube at work).
  - Caching: If 100 people at work visit "google.com", the proxy downloads it
    once and serves it to everyone else from its local storage.

▸ Advanced Concepts
  - Transparent Proxy: Your computer doesn't know it's using a proxy (forced by network).
  - Anonymous Proxy: Hides your IP but tells the server it's a proxy.
  - High Anonymity (Elite) Proxy: Hides your IP and doesn't even say it's a proxy.
  - SOCKS vs. HTTP Proxy:
    - HTTP Proxy: Only understands web traffic (port 80/443).
    - SOCKS Proxy: General purpose, works for any traffic (games, torrents, etc.).

