SECTION 2 ◆ REVERSE PROXY (The Server's Gatekeeper)
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

2.1 THE BASICS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
▸ Simple
  A Reverse Proxy sits in front of the SERVERS.
  When you visit a big site like "Amazon.com", you aren't talking to one single
  server. You are talking to a Reverse Proxy that decides which backend
  server should handle your request.

  [USER] ───► [REVERSE PROXY] ───► [SERVER A]
                                  [SERVER B]
                                  [SERVER C]

▸ Key Features (Intermediate)
  - Load Balancing: Spreads traffic across many servers so none of them crash.
  - Security (WAF): Acts as a shield. Hackers can't see the real servers.
  - SSL Termination: The proxy handles the heavy math of "HTTPS" encryption,
    leaving the backend servers free to just process data.
  - Compression: The proxy shrinks the data (using Gzip or Brotli) before
    sending it to the user, making it load faster.

